Now, let us determine the profit margin of the company:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Profit Margin}&=\frac{\text{Net Income}}{\text{Sales}}\times 100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$17,300}{\$215,000}\times 100\\[12pt]
&={0.08}\times 100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{8\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The profit margin of the company is 8\%.**

To compute the total assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Assets}&=\text{Total Liabilities}+\text{Total Equity}\\[12pt]
&={\$77,000}+{\$59,000}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$136,000}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total asset amounts to \$136,000.**

To compute the Asset Turnover:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Asset Turnover}&=\frac{\text{Sales}}{\text{Total Assets}}\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\text{\$215,000}}{\text{\$136,000}}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{1.58}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The asset turnover of the company is 1.58.**

To compute the total assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Assets}&=\text{Total Liabilities}+\text{Total Equity}\\[12pt]
&={\$77,000}+{\$59,000}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$136,000}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total asset amounts to \$136,000.**

To compute the Asset Turnover:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Equity Multiplier}&=\frac{\text{Total Assets}}{\text{Total Equity}}\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\text{\$136,000}}{\text{\$59,000}}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{1.58}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;;
**The equity multiplier of the company is 2.31.**

To determine the sustainable growth rate, let us first compute the return on equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Return on Equity}&=\text{Profit Margin}\times\text{Total Asset Turnover}\\[5pt]
&\times\text{Equity Multiplier}\\[12pt]
&={8\%}\times{1.58}\times{2.31}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{0.2920}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The return on equity is 0.2920.**

Now, let us compute the retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}-\text{Dividend}\\[12pt]
&={\$17,300}-{\$9,400}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$7,900}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retained earnings is \$7,900.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$7,900}{\$17,300}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.46}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{46\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 46\%.**

To compute the new borrowing, let us determine the cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Cost}&=\text{Sales}-\text{Net Income}\\[12pt]
&={\$215,000}-{\$17,300}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$197,700}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The cost is \$197,700.**

To compute the new borrowing, let us determine the ratio of cost to sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Ratio of Cost to Sales}&=\frac{\text{Cost}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$197,700}{\$215,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.92}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{92\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The ratio of cost to sales is 92\%.**

To compute  the additional Sales using the sustainable growth rate:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Additional Sales}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Sustainable Growth Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$215,000}\times{15.51\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$33,346.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The additional Sales is \$33,346.50.**

To compute  the projected Sales  using the sustainable growth rate:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Sales }&=\text{Sales }+\text{Additional}\\[12pt]
&={\$215,000}+\text{\$33,346.50}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$248,346.50}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Sales is \$248,346.50.**

To compute the projected cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cost}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$248,346.50}\times{92\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$228,478.78}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected cost is \$228,478.78.**

To compute  the projected net income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Income}&=\text{Projected Sales}-\text{Projected Cost}\\[12pt]
&={\$248,346.50}-\text{\$228,478.78}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$19,867.72}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected net income is \$19,867.72.**

Now, let us compute the dividend payout ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend Payout Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Dividend}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$9,400}{\$17,300}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.54}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{54\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The dividend payout ratio is 54\%.**

To compute  the projected Dividends:

&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividends}&=\text{Dividends}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$19,867.72}\times{54\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$10,728.57}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Dividends is \$10,728.57.**

To compute the retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}-\text{Dividends}\\[12pt]
&={\$17,300}-{\$9,400}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$7,900}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retained earnings is \$7,900.**

To compute the projected retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}-\text{Dividends}\\[12pt]
&={\$19,867.72}-{\$10,728.57}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$9,139.15}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected retained earnings is \$9,139.15.**

To compute the difference in the retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Difference}&=\text{Projected Retained Earnings}-\text{Retained Earnings}\\[12pt]
&={\$9,139.15}-{\$7,900}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$1,239.15}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The additional retained earnings is \$1,239.15.**

Based on the computations in the preceding steps, the additional retained earnings are an addition to the total equity of the company. To compute the total equity:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Equity}&=\text{Equity}+\text{Retained Earnings}\\[12pt]
&={\$59,000}+{\$1,239.15}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$60,239.15}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total equity is \$60,239.15.**

Now, let us determine the constant debt-equity ratio of the company:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Debt-to-Equity Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Liabilities}}{\text{Equity}}\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$77,000}{\$59,000}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{1.31}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The debt-to-equity ratio of the company is 1.31.**

Using the constant debt-to-equity ratio of the company, let us determine the new borrowing:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Debt-to-Equity Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Liabilities}}{\text{Equity}}\\[12pt]
1.31&=\frac{\text{Liabilities}}{\$60,239.15}\\[12pt]
\text{Liabilities}&=\boxed{\$78,913.29}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The new borrowing of the company is 78,913.29.**

To determine the internal growth rate, let us first compute total assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Total Assets}&={\text{Total Liability}}+{\text{Total Equity}}\\[12pt]
&={\$77,000}+{\$59,000}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$136,000}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The total assets is \$136,000.**

To determine the internal growth rate, let us first compute the return on assets:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Return on Assets}&=\frac{\text{Net Income}}{\text{Total Assets}}\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$17,300}{\$136,000}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{0.1272}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The return on assets is 0.1272.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$7,900}{\$17,300}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.46}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{46\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 46\%.**

### Compute the projected debt in proportion to the increase in asset.

The proportional increase in debt is calculated by multiplying the projected asset with the debt ratio. The debt ratio should be maintained at 0.57.


$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Debt}&= \text{Debt Ratio} \times \text{Projected Assets}\\[15pt]
&= 0.57 \times \$157,025.60\\[15pt]

&= \boxed{\textbf{\$89,504.59}}

\end{aligned}
$$


Therefore, the projected debt is **$89,504.59**.
